# Substream Architecture

## Two Repos

- **substream-sdk** (`~/substream-sdk`, `github.com/jlin3/substream-sdk`) — Monorepo containing:
  - `@substream/web-sdk` (npm package, browser canvas capture → IVS Real-Time)
  - Unity SDK (C#, WebRTC-based streaming)
  - `IVSBackend/` — Next.js demo/operator backend (the version deployed on Railway at `substream-sdk-production.up.railway.app`)
  - `highlight-service/` — Python FastAPI service for AI highlights (also on Railway)
  - `docs-site/` — Docusaurus, deployed to GitHub Pages
  - `examples/` — web-game-demo, web-viewer

- **substream-platform** (this repo, `github.com/jlin3/substream-platform`) — Production multi-tenant backend:
  - Next.js 15 + Prisma 7 + AWS IVS + Redis + BullMQ
  - Implements the same API contract as IVSBackend (e.g. `/api/streams/web-publish`) so the SDK can point at either backend
  - Adds: multi-tenant orgs/apps/API keys, rate limiting, structured logging, webhook persistence, edge middleware
  - NOT yet deployed to its own Railway service; substream-sdk's IVSBackend is the currently live deployment

## How They Connect

The web SDK and Unity SDK talk to a `backendUrl` over HTTP:
- `POST /api/streams/web-publish` (start stream, get IVS publish token)
- `DELETE /api/streams/web-publish` (stop stream)
- `POST /api/streams/{streamId}/viewer` (get subscribe token)

Both IVSBackend (in substream-sdk) and this platform implement those endpoints. The SDK doesn't care which backend — it's configurable via `backendUrl`.

## Deployment

- Railway project `extraordinary-curiosity` hosts substream-sdk's IVSBackend + Postgres + highlight-service
- substream-platform is NOT deployed yet (needs its own Railway service or separate infra)
- The two repos have separate Prisma schemas and separate databases
